  <section class="essay-opener" id="opener">
    <p class="essay-lede"><span class="essay-lede-proverb">&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t miss the forest for the trees&rdquo;</span> is good advice until it isn&rsquo;t.</p>

    <p>The idiom fits when one is tangled in particulars, unable to see the system at work, and ultimately losing sight of purpose<span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">¹</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">A cognitive narrowing where the focus eclipses everything around it &ndash; useful for threading a needle, costly for navigating a forest.</span><span class="np-refs"><em>AKA:</em> target fixation, tunnel vision, going down the rabbit hole, being stuck in an A-hole, weeds-blindness, can&rsquo;t see the forest for the trees.<br>Aviation accident reports use &ldquo;target fixation&rdquo; for the pilot who locks onto an obstacle and flies into it.</span></span></span>. But abstraction has its own failure mode: the forest saturates the view, and the trees themselves, with all their variation and particularities, are subsumed into a verdant, featureless wash. You have to re-establish contact with reality. As Miroslav Holub wrote in &lsquo;<a href="https://geography.wisc.edu/histcart/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2017/07/brdsht23UPDATED.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Brief Thoughts on Maps</a>,&rsquo; any map will do &mdash; the Hungarian soldiers lost in the Alps navigated home on a map of the Pyrenees. This essay isn&rsquo;t offering you a better map. It&rsquo;s the wood you&rsquo;ve lost contact with, not the cartography. You are <strong>dis</strong>oriented.</p>

    <p>From time to time, you have to put your hands back on the wood.</p>

    <p>Anyone who has worked seriously with hard material &ndash; wood, stone, metal, code &ndash; knows the moment when the system-level view stops helping and you have to get back down to the thing itself.</p>

    <p>A tree is a very slow civilization of fibers and fluids.</p>

    <p>Trees have been solving design and engineering problems a lot longer than us. Several hundred million years, conservatively. Trees are super <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindy_effect" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lindy</a> &mdash; what has lasted tends to keep lasting. The bet is on the branching, not the branch.</p>

    <p>But before there were trees, something else tried to be tall.</p>

    <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure-inbody">
      <img src="/img/essay/consider-the-tree/prototaxites-fossilguy.jpg" alt="A Devonian landscape with several pale Prototaxites columns rising from a low mossy plain crossed by a shallow stream." />
      <figcaption>Devonian landscape with <em>Prototaxites</em> columns. Reconstruction: <a href="https://www.fossilguy.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">fossilguy.com</a>.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <div class="essay-opener-prototaxites">
    <p>Eight-meter trunks rose out of a treeless landscape four hundred million years ago, when nothing on land was bigger than your left thumb. <em><a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mystery-prototaxites-tower-fossils-may-represent-a-newly-discovered-kind-of/">Prototaxites</a></em> &ndash; Protobella, in the privacy of my own head &ndash; confused every paleontologist who tried to sort it. A primitive conifer. An algae. A liverwort. Every fungal phylum on offer. Each category almost worked.</p>

    <p>A Smithsonian botanist named Francis Hueber cut thin sections of those specimens under a microscope for forty years and died in 2019 sure it was a fungus. In <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.aec6277" target="_blank" rel="noopener">2026</a>, new tests on the cell walls turned up lignin-like chemistry and no fungal biomarkers at all.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Chitin is the structural molecule common to all fungi &ndash; insect exoskeletons too.</span></span> Not a fungus. Not a plant. A branch of eukaryotic life that left no descendants.</p>

    <p>A parallel attempt at the tree-form, by a lineage that didn&rsquo;t reach the present. By the end of the Devonian, the columns disappeared. We still don&rsquo;t know why.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Branching solved it. The design kept evolving for hundreds of millions of years. Branches, leaves, shade &ndash; and by then, animals around to use them. Branching was the solution to being tall and photosynthesizing. The cost was knots. The branching solution is older than dinosaurs. <a href="/shelf/#design" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Design thinking</a> is sixty-some years on this planet. Lindy. I mean the literal-biological tree, not Deleuze and Guattari&rsquo;s arborescent strawman. The rhizome (lateral, networked, no apex) was their proposed alternative to the arborescent figure of hierarchy. But the tree they were attacking never matched the actual organism: crown grown lopsided for light, roots tangled with the next tree&rsquo;s, mycorrhizal threads ferrying sugar and signal across species lines underground, sap moving in whichever direction the year demands. What I&rsquo;m describing is closer to what they&rsquo;d call rhizomatic.</p>

    <p>Old trees fall. Some fall this winter. Though, I am noticing where the field trials have been longer.</p>

  </section>

  <section class="essay-section essay-section-alba" id="alba">
    <h2>A tree called Alba</h2>

    <p>Consider the tree.</p>

    <p>One in particular. Ten minutes from my desk, on a slope above Sugar Creek, four white oaks have been standing since before the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Atlanta" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Battle of Atlanta</a>. I walk the dog there. The largest &ndash; <a href="https://meetalba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Alba, the neighborhood calls her</a><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Largest white oak (<em>Quercus alba</em> &ndash; hence the name) inside Atlanta city limits. 69-inch DBH; estimated 200&ndash;250 years old; recently certified healthy by Peter Jenkins of <a href="https://treeinspection.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TreeInspection.com</a>. If preserved, could live another five hundred years. The four oaks sit on a 6-acre parcel off Vaughn Street in Edgewood, rezoned for Planned Development &ndash; Housing in 2007. Source: <a href="https://meetalba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meet Alba</a>.</span></span> &ndash; is around two hundred and fifty years old. Atlanta is one hundred and seventy. A developer wants the lot.</p>
  </section>

