  <section class="essay-section essay-definitions-section" id="vocabulary">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">Vocabulary</div></div>
    <p>A few woodworking terms.</p>

    <dl class="essay-definitions">
      <dt><strong>rive</strong> <span class="essay-definitions-meta">/raɪv/ &middot; verb.</span></dt>
      <dd>To split wood along the grain with a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Au1TbIyLcPU" target="_blank" rel="noopener">froe and a mallet</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">¹</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">Roy Underhill working a log on <em>The Woodwright&rsquo;s Shop</em> &ndash; froe, axe, drawknife, no power. Underhill favors simple tools and is wary of modern ones on principle; the simple ones let the wood do more of the deciding.</span></span></span>. Old Norse <em>rífa,</em> &ldquo;to tear, scratch&rdquo; &ndash; same root as <em>rift, riven, reef.</em> You aren&rsquo;t cutting the wood. You&rsquo;re persuading it to come apart along a line it was already going to take if you waited long enough. Stronger than a sawn board, because the fibers stay continuous. The downside is you can&rsquo;t rive anything that didn&rsquo;t intend to split. When people say they&rsquo;re &ldquo;working with the grain,&rdquo; they usually mean cutting along the direction of the fibers, not against them. Riving is the only technique that does what the phrase actually says: you don&rsquo;t cut along the grain, you let the grain choose where the cut goes. Modern English carries this forward in another direction: a <em>riven</em> family, a <em>riven</em> country. The word didn&rsquo;t move; we just stopped noticing where it came from.</dd>

      <dt><strong>green wood</strong></dt>
      <dd>Wood still alive, or recently so. Moisture content high enough that the cells haven&rsquo;t shrunk back. Moves while you work it. Keeps moving for months after you&rsquo;re done. Carpenters who only know kiln-dried boards treat green wood like a problem; anyone who works it learns the movement is information.</dd>

      <dt><strong>plane</strong> <span class="essay-definitions-meta">/pleɪn/ &middot; noun, verb.</span></dt>
      <dd>A hand tool: a sharpened blade set in a body of wood or iron, tuned to shave a thin curl off a board. Also what you do with it. Not the geometry kind, not the airplane kind. The thing on a workbench. In the right hands, it leaves a surface smoother than sandpaper ever will. In the wrong hands, it digs a hole.</dd>

      <dt><strong>grain</strong></dt>
      <dd>The direction the wood fibers go. Sometimes obvious, sometimes not. Reading the grain is the difference between a clean cut and a torn-up surface; it&rsquo;s also the difference between a workpiece that holds and a workpiece that splits.</dd>

      <dt><strong>heartwood</strong></dt>
      <dd>The dense inner core of a mature tree, darker than the wood around it. Dead, but load-bearing: it has stopped growing, stopped moving water, and become the part that holds the rest of the tree up. The living wood is the thin layer at the edge.</dd>

      <dt><strong>knot</strong></dt>
      <dd>Where a branch grew out of the trunk, and the tree buried it under ring after ring of new wood, the way an oyster embalms a speck of grit in layers of pearl. Cut a knot the wrong way and your plane skips. The defect is the tree&rsquo;s memory.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Rope-knots are tied; wood-knots formed. Tied knots come from intention. Formed knots come from biography. Same word, different reading.</span></span></dd>

      <dt><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reaction_wood" target="_blank" rel="noopener">reaction wood</a></strong></dt>
      <dd>Wood the tree produced under load: a trunk leaning into a slope, a sapling pushed by its neighbor. The loaded side lays down different fibers. The board looks normal. It behaves badly. You can&rsquo;t see reaction wood until you cut it, and sometimes not until it warps in your shop a month later.</dd>

      <dt><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abscission" target="_blank" rel="noopener">abscission</a></strong></dt>
      <dd>The tree&rsquo;s mechanism for shedding a branch cleanly: a separation zone forms at the petiole, on the tree&rsquo;s side, and seals the wound with a layer of cork cells before the branch drops. Tree-initiated, tree-timed, wound closed before exposure.</dd>
    </dl>

    <p>A tree cannot <a href="/shelf/#bullshit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">bullshit</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="record">
    <figure class="essay-image-slot">
