    <h2>Record</h2>

    <p>Wood records. Each ring dates a year of growth. Each knot dates a branching event. Each scar dates an injury and the response to it. Trees keep no spreadsheets. They write in grain, ring, knot, and scar. Reading a board is reading a biography.</p>

    {# [REDLINE — sentence after "planes the sapwood" needs Lee's hand.
       Current "It skates uselessly across the knot" is conceptually wrong:
       knots don't get skated across, that's clear sapwood. At a knot the
       motion is encounter — less often skates, more often catches/crashes;
       can take the wind out of you when in flow. Claude drafts kept stacking
       carpentry verbs onto an institutional sentence and producing slop.
       Lee writes the replacement. Lines after stay as-is. #}
    <p>Communities are not inert inputs. Institutions are not dimensionally stable. Incentives swell and shrink seasonally. Political moisture content changes. Programs move after installation.</p>

    <p>Institutions carry the same kind of record, and most of it slips past the tools they prefer. What gets filed planes the sapwood. It catches at the knot and reads nothing. The consultants flown in with decks plane the same sapwood for more money. A dated knot &ndash; a near-bankruptcy in 2002, an executive transition that swapped the nameplate not the decisions, an impact figure recycled since 2010, an annual report written for what the funder expected to be true &ndash; bears load the way heartwood does.</p>

    <p>Institutionalized procedures, obsolete-seeming roles, accumulated tacit norms &ndash; these are not organizational fat to be cut. They are the heartwood. Organizations that try to stay metabolically active all the way through their structure &ndash; all sapwood, no heartwood &ndash; are trading structural integrity for short-term nutrient throughput. They&rsquo;ll grow fast and blow over.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">The tree doesn&rsquo;t know it&rsquo;s doing this. Abscission isn&rsquo;t a decision; phloem doesn&rsquo;t allocate. The mechanism runs below the level of agency. Reading the diagnosis doesn&rsquo;t change the mechanism &ndash; only how an organization responds to it. The frame names what&rsquo;s happening. It doesn&rsquo;t tell you what to cut.</span></span></p>

    <p>Most of Alba is dead.</p>

    <p>Most of the air came from things buried before they could decay.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Respiration and decay consume roughly 99% of the oxygen photosynthesis produces. Atmospheric O&#8322; accumulated, over billions of years, only because a small fraction of organic carbon got buried in sediments before it could be respired back to CO&#8322;. Catling &amp; Claire (2005), <em>How Earth&rsquo;s atmosphere evolved to an oxic state.</em></span></span></p>

    <p>You hear the knot in stories. You usually learn what you really need to know at the bar, after the conference. Or in DMs. Or when the recording stops. Not in meetings.</p>

    <p>Operators know. The operating narrative is everything &ndash; the story that connects operations to effectiveness, whatever the values and mission statement say. As Monika Krause argues in <em><a href="https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/G/bo17888868.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Good Project</a></em>, most NGOs have their narrative wrong. Mission and operations drift apart. The tacit knowledge that actually runs the place lives scattered in heads.</p>

    <p>An organization that cannot read its own record cannot locate its own knots. Non-profits and for-profits alike. No one sees the whole story from within &ndash; an <a href="https://anxiaomina.substack.com/p/elephant-problems-the-limitations" target="_blank" rel="noopener">elephant problem</a>.</p>

    <p>Atlanta started branding itself &ldquo;<a href="https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/why-atlanta-known-city-forest/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City in a Forest</a>&rdquo; mid-twentieth century. American Forests put the metro region at 48% tree canopy in 1974; Georgia Tech put the city limits at 46.5% in 2018.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Georgia Tech Center for Spatial Planning Analytics and Visualization, <em>2018 City of Atlanta Urban Tree Canopy Assessment</em>; American Forests, <em>Regional Ecosystem Analysis: Atlanta Metropolitan Area</em> (2001). 1974 figure is metro region, 2018 figure is city limits &ndash; not a clean trend line.</span></span> The decade ending 2018 shed roughly 150 acres a year, mostly to private redevelopment. The cluster of global-health institutions whose campuses sit a few miles apart here &ndash; I was at <a href="https://www.sph.emory.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Rollins</a> for grad school, in the middle of it &ndash; runs the same dynamic at organizational scale.</p>

