  <section class="essay-section" id="knots-self">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">I work with knots</div></div>
    <h2>I work with knots</h2>

    <p>I've gathered a set of useful tools along the way, and made a few of my own. Most of my consulting tools are for handling <em>knots</em>: places where the grain runs in several directions at once, and the next cut is not obvious.</p>

    <p>The cut depends on the knot. Reading one starts mechanically &ndash; how it formed, how the grain runs through it, where it fails.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="how-knots">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">How I think about knots</div></div>
    <h2>How I think about knots</h2>

    <p>A knot begins as a branch &ndash; and the branch began as a reach for light.</p>

    <p>Each year, with the turn of the seasons, the tree lays down another ring of wood around its core, just beneath the bark. Slowly the trunk thickens around the living branch, engulfing it ring by ring. Year after year, ring on ring, knot on knot.</p>

    <p>Sped up, the tree would look animate. Bark faintly crackling along the trunk&rsquo;s slow swell, microfissures opening into warm, gnarled retreats for insects. Pale new wood lapping over the last with each rainy season. Meanwhile the buried branch, still carrying water up through the trunk to leaves beyond the bark, keeps drinking.</p>

    <p>A knot is engulfed tissue, still drinking.</p>

    <p>A sawyer reads for them. Bark bumps, branch scars, the way the tree leaned. The log gets oriented on the carriage accordingly.</p>

    <hr class="essay-divider" />

    <p>The tree keeps growing toward the sun, laying down new road each spring on its journey toward the sky (while the weather's good for construction). Inside and out, the tree works the season for what it can get. Moisture, warmth, and light.</p>

    <p>At a knot, the grain takes the long way around &ndash; bending the way spacetime bends around a black hole.</p>

    <p>Around the knot, the fibers crowd together, cross paths, switch direction without warning. Sometimes the wood hardens around the knot, glassy and resinous, and your chisel chatters across it like a skipped record. Sometimes the fibers tear loose all at once and leave a divot where a smooth cut was supposed to be. Wood that read clear a few inches ago judders under the plane like a shopping cart with one bad wheel.</p>

    <p>Worst case, the plane meets a knot the way a car meets a telephone pole.</p>

    <p>This is usually where people begin blaming their tools.</p>

    <p>The knot holds harder than the wood around it under certain loads, and fails first across the grain.</p>

    <p>You learn to read ahead a little. The habit carries.</p>

    <hr class="essay-divider" />

    <p>Hard problems aren't hard because nobody is smart enough or working hard enough. It&rsquo;s in the nature of a living system to make knots. No knots, no branches. No branches, no peaches, nesting places, or afternoon shade. No shade, no tree to fall asleep against.</p>

    <p>You don&rsquo;t fix a gnarled oak. You learn to read what the tree has written, reckon with how the grain bends around the knot, and follow the cut the grain itself wants.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="common-knots">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">Common knots and useful tools</div></div>
    <h2>Common knots and useful tools</h2>

    <p>To know which tool to reach for, we have to examine the knot.</p>

    <p>A knot is not a problem category or an implementation barrier. It is a recurring configuration of legitimate pressures that cannot all be satisfied at once. The point isn&rsquo;t to &ldquo;solve&rdquo; the knot. The point is to recognize its shape early.</p>

    <h3>The problem with wicked problems</h3>

    <figure class="essay-figure-inbody">
      <img
        src="/img/essay/consider-the-tree/concepts-become-things.webp"
        alt="A photograph of geometric solids - spheres, cones, cylinders, cubes, prisms - arranged in a desert landscape, overlaid with the meme caption 'Everybody gangsta until concepts become things.'"
      />
      <figcaption>Found meme. Original artwork: <em>Metamorphosis</em>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbert_Bayer" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Herbert Bayer</a> (1936).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>&ldquo;Wicked problems&rdquo; is a frame for hard problems. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/14494035.2019.1617971">It&rsquo;s been used too many ways to mean much.</a> Once I've called something wicked, I know it's hard. I don't know what kind of hard, or what to do next.</p>

    <p>A better diagnostic names the knot, and the cut that fits it. A few I work with often:</p>

    <p><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Goodhart&rsquo;s Law</a>.</strong> <em>(<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campbell%27s_law" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Campbell&rsquo;s Law</a> &middot; Tyranny of Metrics)</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Charles Goodhart&rsquo;s original 1975 formulation: <em>&ldquo;Any observed statistical regularity will tend to collapse once pressure is placed upon it for control purposes.&rdquo;</em> The Strathern compression is the line that travels: <em>&ldquo;When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure.&rdquo;</em></span></span> An indicator starts as protection against drift, then becomes the thing the system optimizes. Staff know which number matters; they learn to game it whether or not the work moves with it. The number is sapwood. The actual grain runs somewhere underneath. The cut that fits is to rotate the measures, triangulate with what the indicator can&rsquo;t see, and deliberately leave the number under-optimized.</p>

    <p><strong>Capability Trap.</strong> <em>(Andrews, Pritchett &amp; Woolcock)</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Matt Andrews, Lant Pritchett &amp; Michael Woolcock, <em><a href="https://library.oapen.org/handle/20.500.12657/31857" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Building State Capability: Evidence, Analysis, Action</a></em> (Oxford, 2017). Pairs with <em>premature load bearing</em> &ndash; the related failure mode where a new mechanism is asked to carry weight before the underlying capacity exists.</span></span> Organizations learn to look functional before they learn to function. Plans, dashboards, organograms, all visible; the ordinary work still depends on improvisation. This is reaction wood. The boards lay down straight, and warp a month after delivery. The cut that fits is fewer formal commitments and permission to under-report polish while the real competence forms underneath.</p>

    <p><strong>Isomorphic Mimicry.</strong> <em>(DiMaggio &amp; Powell &middot; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seeing_Like_a_State" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Seeing Like a State</a>)</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Paul DiMaggio &amp; Walter Powell, &ldquo;The Iron Cage Revisited: Institutional Isomorphism and Collective Rationality in Organizational Fields,&rdquo; <em>American Sociological Review</em> 48 (1983): 147&ndash;160. Three mechanisms: coercive (regulation, funder demands), mimetic (copying perceived legitimate forms under uncertainty), normative (professional training and credentialing). The development-policy variant &ndash; <em>isomorphic mimicry</em> &ndash; comes out of the Building State Capability work and emphasizes mimetic adoption of form without the underlying capacity.</span></span> Institutions import the form of legitimacy from somewhere else because that&rsquo;s what funders and peers recognize. Inside, the real decisions still travel through an older informal architecture. The surface grain was planed to match the room. What&rsquo;s load-bearing was grown in a different forest. The cut that fits is to keep enough imported form to stay legitimate and let the working structure be shaped by the actual load.</p>

    <p><strong>Trust on Demand.</strong> <em>(Trapped Priors)</em> A split that opened in a different cut, years ago, and never closed. Institutions ask for trust where prior experience has trained people to withhold it. Officials hear distrust as misinformation; communities hear urgency as another request to carry risk for someone else&rsquo;s plan. The cut that fits is repair before persuasion &ndash; name prior harms, narrow promises, permit refusal.</p>

    <p><strong>Evaluation Theatre.</strong> <em>(Innovation Theater &middot; <a href="/shelf/#bullshit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cargo Cult Science</a>)</em> The grain direction was declared in the terms of reference. Nobody read the actual wood. Terms of reference get drafted toward a known landing; inception meetings narrow the questions; everyone in the room already knows which answers are safe. Findings get praised; nothing consequential changes. The cut that fits is to precommit to decisions the findings can change, and to fund the negative results.</p>

    <p>Most real work has several of these going at once. A lot of what I do is figuring out which cut fits which knot in front of us. The diagnostic doesn&rsquo;t come from above. You put your hands back on the wood. Alba is still standing.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="where-it-breaks">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">Where it breaks</div></div>
    <h2>Where it breaks</h2>

    <p>Three things the tree can&rsquo;t do that break the theory.</p>

    <p><strong>Can&rsquo;t relocate.</strong> Arboreal theory is implicitly a theory of <em>site-committed</em> organizations &mdash; ones that have sunk their roots so deep into a particular market, geography, regulatory environment, or customer base that exit is not a live option. CODIT works because the tree cannot abandon the wound; it must wall it off and grow around it. Organizations that <em>can</em> relocate just leave &mdash; they don&rsquo;t develop the compartmentalization discipline. This is why the theory predicts IBM better than it predicts a SaaS startup: the startup pivots away from the wound, the mainframe division has to wall it off and continue. Mobility dissolves the selection pressure that makes arboreal resilience adaptive. What survives breakage when you can exit is different from what survives when you can&rsquo;t &mdash; it&rsquo;s not toughness, it&rsquo;s optionality. Different organism entirely.</p>

    <p><strong>No intentions.</strong> The tree executes CODIT without knowing what CODIT is. Abscission is not a decision; phloem redistribution is not resource allocation with a memo. The mechanism runs below the level of agency. The moment you map this onto an organization, you get a theory that describes what <em>should</em> happen if the organization were running its own biology correctly &mdash; but organizations can read the theory, anticipate the diagnosis, and game it. A division that knows it&rsquo;s going to be abscised can sabotage the compartmentalization wall. A manager who recognizes the phloem-flow pattern can intercept the nutrient stream. The arboreal theory is most accurate for organizations that <em>don&rsquo;t know</em> they&rsquo;re running it &mdash; mature bureaucracies, late-stage institutions, anything where the biology has become sufficiently externalized and forgotten that it runs like metabolism rather than strategy. Applied to self-aware, theoretically-literate organizations, it becomes a script that clever actors exploit.</p>

    <p><strong>One body plan.</strong> Every structural inference the theory makes &mdash; that wounds propagate inward before walling off, that energy flows from roots through trunk to canopy, that leaf sacrifice is peripheral before it&rsquo;s central &mdash; depends on the tree having a canonical topology. Root-trunk-branch-leaf is not arbitrary; it&rsquo;s load-bearing for the whole model. Organizations don&rsquo;t have this. A matrix organization has no trunk. A holocracy has no canopy. A networked organization has no clear periphery to sacrifice first. The body-plan assumption smuggles in a hidden organizational form: the classic hierarchy, functional or divisional, with clear center-periphery geometry. The arboreal theory is secretly a theory of <em>that</em> organization wearing botanical clothing. For anything outside that topology, the spatial intuitions break down &mdash; you can&rsquo;t say which branch is peripheral when there&rsquo;s no branch, only a mesh.</p>
  </section>

